Subject: emacsclient: replace built-in 'edit'
Message-Id: <8538125ca0f8fa31-0-artemis@nixos-framework>

Not sure what the best approach is for this. We should encourage 'write' for
pure additions, whilst this should feel more like a diff. However, LLMs can
struggle to write diffs, since reproducing the exact previous content is not
well suited to their abilities.

There have been some interesting experiments, e.g. I like the idea of
https://blog.can.ac/2026/02/12/the-harness-problem/ to tag lines with their
number and a short hash of their content. However, that requires more extensive
changes to `read` as well...

My current thinking:

 - Have `read` return a set of `spans`:
   - Each span refers to a particular section of the buffer
   - We can use a bunch of heuristics to make them more meaningful/useful
   - Tree-sitter is an obvious source of spans
   - A simple fallback is to provide spans covering each 1/Nth of the buffer
   - Each span has an ID, which includes a hash of its content
     - The hash only needs to be, say, 4 chars; just truncate
     - If the span's contents have changed since the LLM read it, the hash won't
       match.
 - Edit operations must be given a span ID, to edit or replace, etc.
 - Also provide a 'narrow' tool, which will narrow the buffer to a given
   span ID, and return a new list of spans from inside that.
   - Even better: take a list of span IDs, to support sub-spans!
 - Future work: extend `read` and `write` to accept span IDs to narrow their
   buffers!
